                    <title>ALL done</title>
                    <text>&lt;b&gt;Summary&lt;/b&gt;
Two carbons enter the TCA cycle in the form of acetyl-CoA.

Two carbons are released during the TCA cycle in the form of CO2.  Note that the carbons that enter the cycle are not released during the first turn of the cycle, but are released on subsequent cycles.

The oxidation of acetate to CO2 is an 8 electron oxidation.

The energy released by this oxidation is stored as follows:

     3 NADH are produced, carrying a total of 6 electrons.
     1 FADH2 is produced, carrying 2 electrons.
     1 high-energy phosphate compound (GTP) is produced.

This circular pathway ends with the production of the starting intermediate in the pathway - oxaloacetate.



